    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Codonoboea rugosa improperly are experiencing nausea, inducing nausea, causing vomiting, and causing dizziness due to its toxic compounds, specifically the cardenolides, which can be toxic if ingested in large quantities or for extended periods. This plant contains cardenolides, which are known to be toxic to humans and can cause gastrointestinal disturbances, including nausea and vomiting. The improper use of Codonoboea rugosa may also lead to dizziness due to its effects on the nervous system. If ingested, the cardenolides can cause irritation to the digestive tract and lead to symptoms such as nausea and vomiting. Ingesting large amounts of Codonoboea rugosa can lead to more severe symptoms and potentially life-threatening complications.",
    "uses": "Codonoboea rugosa is a plant species native to Borneo, and while information on its medicinal uses is limited, it is reported to have potential applications in traditional medicine. Traditionally, the plant is used in herbal remedies to treat various ailments, including fever and rheumatism. The plant's properties are believed to possess anti-inflammatory and antimicrobial properties, making it a subject of interest in modern pharmacological research. However, more studies are needed to confirm its efficacy and safety for human consumption. Further research is required to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential uses of Codonoboea rugosa.",
    "taxonomy": "Codonoboea rugosa is classified as a species of flowering plant in the family Apocynaceae. This plant belongs to the genus Codonoboea, which is a group of flowering plants native to Southeast Asia. The Apocynaceae family is a large and diverse group of flowering plants commonly known as dogbane or oleander family. The classification of Codonoboea rugosa is further divided into the kingdom Plantae and the phylum Angiospermophyta. At the most basic level, the classification of Codonoboea rugosa is also divided into the domain Eukarya.",
    "benefits": "Codonoboea rugosa is known to have various health benefits due to its unique properties. The plant is rich in antioxidants and has anti-inflammatory properties, which can help reduce inflammation and protect against cell damage. Additionally, Codonoboea rugosa has been traditionally used to treat fever, cough, and other respiratory issues. Its antimicrobial properties also make it effective in fighting off bacterial and fungal infections. Further research is needed to fully explore the health benefits of Codonoboea rugosa.",
    "parts": "Codonoboea rugosa is a plant species that is native to Borneo. The medicinal parts of Codonoboea rugosa have been used in traditional medicine for their various health benefits. The leaves and roots of the plant are commonly used due to their high concentration of bioactive compounds. These compounds have been found to possess antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, and antimicrobial properties, making the plant useful for treating various ailments. However, further research is needed to fully understand the medicinal properties and potential uses of Codonoboea rugosa.",
    "intro": "Codonoboea rugosa is a species of flowering plant in the family Gesneriaceae, native to the tropical regions of Asia. The plant has been traditionally used in herbal medicine for its various health benefits, including its anti-inflammatory, antibacterial, and antifungal properties, which can aid in wound healing and the treatment of respiratory infections. The bioactive constituents of Codonoboea rugosa include flavonoids, alkaloids, and saponins, which are responsible for its medicinal properties. In traditional medicine, the plant is often made into teas, infusions, or tinctures, which are used to treat a range of ailments, including fever, cough, and sore throats."
